As I said, it's a matter of my heart.  But please, if it is in the Bible, what verse is it in?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>That seems a little too easy for me. There really isn't a need for faith anymore if God would just reveal Himself physically to everyone and say, &quot;Here is your proof people, now believe.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Why is blind faith a requirement for belief?  It wasn't a requirement in the Old Testament.  Isn't it possible that this is just a time of testing to sift out those who are able to believe without physical proof?  The Bible talks about us storing up treasures in Heaven, which would indicate there will be some kind of distinguishment between those who were most faithful to God in this life and those who were least.  Of course this is going into mysteries we know nothing about which concerns things like what will Heaven be like, what will our roles in Heaven be like, are there going to be certain kinds of ways to distinguish people from one another and if so what?  It's possible that those who believed through blind faith will have a status different than those who had to have physical proof.<br>
<br>
But this is all speculation and theory and I'm not saying anything definite because I know it's not told to us nor explained and I could be totally wrong and that's okay.  The reason I posed the question in this thread is because I don't know the answer but it's been something in the back of my mind for a long time that from time to time I just start to wonder about.  It doesn't affect my salvation or the importance I feel for us to continue reaching out to others with the Gospel of Christ.  It's just one of those things that makes me feel a little disconcerted at times and it bugs me that I don't have the answers.<br>
<br>
Maybe there won't be a chance for those who die without Christ.  Maybe they don't have a prayer, even if they believe once they see Him and would devote their entire beings to Him at that point.  I can't say, I just don't know.  My heart hopes not, my heart wants to see everyone come to Christ.  My heart hopes that everyone is given every possible opportunity up to the very last second of being thrown into the lake of fire mentioned towards the end of Revelation.  I hate suffering and it breaks my heart to see people lost without Christ.  If people are not given a chance after they die, then this is an area where I truly don't understand God and His reasoning.  I want to understand Him and I imagine that if it were me who decided, I would give people every opportunity, even after death.  But them my intelligence and understanding of the universe both spiritual and unspiritual is severely microscopic compared to God's.  I know enough to know I can't see things the way He sees things.  But I do wish I could understand His reasoning behind things.  More than anything, I would pray for more wisdom to understand the things of God.  To be able to understand and fathom untold mysteries.  There are times when I get annoyed at my limitations as a fallen mortal being who can still so easily fall into temptation and sin.<br>
<br>
Is it Biblical or Unbiblical, I simply don't know, that's why I'm asking the question.  And I don't think God minds me asking, because certainly He knows it's been a question on my heart and in my head for a long time and one I simply have never said outloud.  So whether I ask it outloud or not, He already knows I was thinking about it and wondering and not sure and He understands the pain my heart feels at the thought of people after dying and realizing who He is and being willing to worship Him forever being thrown into the lake of fire.  My heart feels in conflict with this one mainstream popular Christian thought.  I wish I could build a time machine and go back in time and pose my question to Jesus or Paul.  I wouldn't mind the Lord giving me an audible answer, although I admit I might freak out if I ever heard Him speak out loud as it's something I've never heard before and I would imagine there would be much majesty, power and might in His voice.<br>
<br>
But anyhoo... <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center">**********************************************<br>
